{"award_age":61.0,"bio_image":"full\/cda7b5aa32e880d65af181a63ff221ab706910f4.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1920-03-11T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/9\/9c\/Nicolaas_Bloembergen_1981.jpg\/220px-Nicolaas_Bloembergen_1981.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nicolaas_Bloembergen","mini_bio":"<p><b>Nicolaas Bloembergen<\/b> (born March 11, 1920) is a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Netherlands\" title=\"Netherlands\">Dutch<\/a>-<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">American<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Physics\" title=\"Physics\">physicist<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_laureate\" title=\"Nobel laureate\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Nobel laureate<\/a>.<\/p><p>He received his <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Doctor_of_Philosophy\" title=\"Doctor of Philosophy\">Ph.D.<\/a> degree from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Leiden\" title=\"University of Leiden\" class=\"mw-redirect\">University of Leiden<\/a> under <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cornelis_Jacobus_Gorter\" title=\"Cornelis Jacobus Gorter\">Cor Gorter<\/a> in 1948; while pursuing his PhD at Harvard, Bloembergen also worked part-time as a graduate research assistant for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edward_Mills_Purcell\" title=\"Edward Mills Purcell\">Edward Mills Purcell<\/a> at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/MIT\" title=\"MIT\" class=\"mw-redirect\">MIT<\/a> Radiation Laboratory <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"http:\/\/nobelprize.org\/nobel_prizes\/physics\/laureates\/1981\/bloembergen-autobio.html\">[1]<\/a>. He became a professor at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_University\" title=\"Harvard University\">Harvard University<\/a> in Applied Physics.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nicolaas_Bloembergen#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was brought up in the Protestant household.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nicolaas_Bloembergen#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Bloembergen enrolled in 1938 at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Utrecht\" title=\"University of Utrecht\" class=\"mw-redirect\">University of Utrecht<\/a> to study physics. Bloembergen left the war ravaged Netherlands in 1945 to pursue graduate studies at Harvard University. Six weeks before his arrival, Harvard Professor <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edward_M._Purcell\" title=\"Edward M. Purcell\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Edward M. Purcell<\/a> (along with his graduate students Torrey and Pound) discovered <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nuclear_magnetic_resonance\" title=\"Nuclear magnetic resonance\">nuclear magnetic resonance<\/a>. Bloembergen was hired to develop a first NMR machine. While at Harvard he enjoyed classes from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Julian_Schwinger\" title=\"Julian Schwinger\">J. Schwinger<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Hasbrouck_Van_Vleck\" title=\"John Hasbrouck Van Vleck\">J. H. van Vleck<\/a>, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edwin_C._Kemble\" title=\"Edwin C. Kemble\">E. C. Kemble<\/a>. His thesis <i>Nuclear Magnetic Relaxation<\/i> was submitted in Leiden, where he passed qualifying criteria. After a brief postdoctoral appointment with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/C._J._Gorter\" title=\"C. J. Gorter\" class=\"mw-redirect\">C. J. Gorter<\/a> in the Netherlands, he joined Harvard where he was named a junior fellow of Society of Fellows in 1949 and associate professor in 1951.<\/p><p>In 1958, he became a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Naturalized_citizen\" title=\"Naturalized citizen\" class=\"mw-redirect\">naturalized citizen<\/a> of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">United States<\/a>.<\/p><p>He was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lorentz_Medal\" title=\"Lorentz Medal\">Lorentz Medal<\/a> in 1978. Bloembergen shared the 1981 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Arthur_Leonard_Schawlow\" title=\"Arthur Leonard Schawlow\">Arthur Schawlow<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Kai_Manne_Boerje_Siegbahn\" title=\"Kai Manne Boerje Siegbahn\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Kai Siegbahn<\/a> for their work in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Laser\" title=\"Laser\">laser<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Spectroscopy\" title=\"Spectroscopy\">spectroscopy<\/a>. Bloembergen and Schawlow investigated properties of matter undetectable without lasers. He had earlier modified the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Maser\" title=\"Maser\">maser<\/a> of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charles_Townes\" title=\"Charles Townes\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Charles Townes<\/a>. Bloembergen serves on the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Arizona\" title=\"University of Arizona\">University of Arizona<\/a> faculty.<\/p><p>Bloembergen belongs to prolific <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/J._J._Thomson\" title=\"J. J. Thomson\">J. J. Thomson<\/a> academic lineage tree, following in footsteps of other <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Prize\">Nobel<\/a> Laureates beginning with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lord_Rayleigh\" title=\"Lord Rayleigh\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Lord Rayleigh<\/a> (Physics Nobel Prize in 1904) and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/J._J._Thomson\" title=\"J. J. Thomson\">J. J. Thomson<\/a> (Nobel 1906), and continued with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ernest_Rutherford\" title=\"Ernest Rutherford\">Ernest Rutherford<\/a> (<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Chemistry\">Nobel Prize in Chemistry<\/a> 1908), <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Owen_Richardson\" title=\"Owen Richardson\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Owen Richardson<\/a> (Physics Nobel, 1928) and finally Bloembergen's advisor, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Edward_Mills_Purcell\" title=\"Edward Mills Purcell\">Edward Purcell<\/a> (Physics Nobel 1952). Prof. Bloembergen is a member of the Board of Sponsors of The <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http:\/\/www.thebulletin.org\">Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists<\/a> and Honorary Editor of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Journal_of_Nonlinear_Optical_Physics_%26_Materials\" title=\"Journal of Nonlinear Optical Physics &amp; Materials\">Journal of Nonlinear Optical Physics &amp; Materials<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nicolaas_Bloembergen#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> His other influences included <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Van_Vleck\" title=\"John Van Vleck\" class=\"mw-redirect\">John Van Vleck<\/a> (Physics Nobel 1977) and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Percy_Bridgman\" title=\"Percy Bridgman\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Percy Bridgman<\/a> (Physics Nobel 1946).<\/p>","name":"Nicolaas Bloembergen","place_of_birth":"Dordrecht ,  Netherlands","place_of_death":null,"text":"Nicolaas Bloembergen ,  born in the Netherlands , Physics, 1981","year":1981.0}